snippet.textDisplay:
So many details and tips missed out.

I wouldn’t use that much flour unless you need to make two loafs, more dough means more kneading which can be hard work.

For 1 loaf

500g strong bread flour
295ml warm water (be exact)
1x Table spoon of olive oil
Teaspoon of salt.
7g sachet of yeast

I usually just pour the flour in a big bowl. Put the yeast to one side of the bowl and the salt to the other and mix them in a bit. The salt reduces the effects of the yeast if in direct contact of each other.

Make a well in the flour and poor 3 quarters of the water and oil. Mix and gradually add rest of the water until you have a ball of dough.

Oil your surface or use some flour. The dough needs aggressive kneading for at least 30 mins and should become quite stretchy. The trick is to hold a piece up to the light, stretch it a bit and if you can see the light like a window pane you’re good to go. This video cuts at 1.41 and shows the dough again after kneading which the viewer does not see. Notice the texture difference.

Rub some olive oil around the bowl and leave the dough in there with a damp tea towel or cling film over the top. This stops the dough from crisping.

Leave for an 1 to 2 hours in a warmish place. (Cupboard)

It doesn’t always double in size, depends on the temp of your room and how well you kneaded it.

Once risen, knock the dough back to remove the air out of it. Now shape your dough into the type of loaf you want. Grease a baking tray and place your shaped dough onto it ready to go in the oven. Cover for another 1.5 hours or until roughly doubled in size.

Pre heat oven to 200 degrees C for fan oven.

If you want crusty bread, leave a tray at the bottom of your oven and allow it to heat up. Once you’ve placed the dough in the over pour roughly half a cup of water into the tray and close the door. The steam created causes the bread to crust.

Leave for exactly 36 minutes. In total. Turn down oven to 180 degrees c after 10 minutes of baking and leave at that temp for the remaining time.

Remove and leave on a wire rack for half an hour before eating and you should have some decent bread if you follow those instructing.

Hope I helped.

snippet.textDisplay:
PEOPLE: Start trying your best wherever you live to get on the internet and buy flour and bulks of yeast, as well as baking soda (bicarbonate of soda) and baking powder. All the items needed to make some form of bread. The latter two will allow you to make non-yeast bread like Soda Bread. If you have an older relative that makes bread, but doesn't understand the internet help them out. We're all in this together. Where I live the low price bulk yeasts are all being sold out, but are popping up on Amazon and Ebay at 3x or more the price. This is also THE time to start learning how to make Levain, as that needs time to be ready and may be the only form of yeast that may be available. Just don't tell KAREN!
Good Luck and be safe. I am sending love to all of you around the world.

snippet.textDisplay: other option would be adding the water drop per drop(takes you around 3minutes and u end up with a slightly drier dough but that also reduces the bakingtime which saves nutrients and if your into nutrients you should open the oven every few minutes for a fewseconds to help let the moisture escape. this reduces the baking time too)  if you cant or dont wanna use yeast use a knifetip of salt grinded  to powder and dont kneed(dont compress the dough at all) but fold it invery carefully(use dont even need to let the dough rest longer using this technique. 1 hour should be enough i guess. it makes a huge difference in flavor and it raises a little better. i really wanna add is that yeast reduces the protein content of the dough since it digests a part of it. the reason people use yeast is because its easier to digest this way but you obviously have to eat more/more frequently to reach your desired protein intake^^ and yea i guess that why many cultures enjoy flatbreads they are done quickly and u lose the least nutrients. greetings haha thought id wright something usefull today ^^ last thing i wanna mention is that if you never tried it eat raw dough(meaning only water flour..and salt to taste and see how little you now need to feel "full" and nurished
